<br>
This caused a number of things as a consequence.  First off, Monks soloed the best of all the pure melee classes.  I would argue, better than was really reasonable given the restrictions other pure melees had to deal with.  Secondly, higher end Monks were exceptionally good at doing things such as rampage tanking because their ability to FD coupled with high avoidance and the ability to take damage like a Warrior made them excell in this area.  And finally, there were times and places where the Monk tanked equally as well as a Warrior, so rather than bothering to control aggro and let the class that was 'supposed' to be tanking tank, the Monk would just go ahead and do it.<br>
<br>
Some changes were in order, as the game stood at that time.  Many people think what was done was too extreme and impacted the lower end Monk more dramatically than the higher end Monk.  This seems to hold some truth, how much is hard to say.<br>
<br>
However, something else occured around the same time that changed the game dramatically.  PoP was released and experience was nerfed game wide.  No zone outside of PoP is really good experience for a character that is level 60 or beyond anymore.  Which means most people hunt in PoP.  And in PoP, even if Monk mitigation had remained unchanged, it's doubtful Monks would have had the tankability they had previously.  The mobs hit too hard and total HP is just as important if not more so as your AC.<br>
<br>
In retrospect, it would probably have made more sense to introduce PoP first, see what that did to the game dynamics, and then decide how do deal with adjusting Monks, if any adjustment was still needed.   <p>The Man in Black: We are men of action, lies do not become us. <br>
